<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators are compromising 
on a spending bill that gives president bush less than he requested 
for nuclear weapons production but more than he wants to correct 
environmental damage at the arms plants 
the measure earmarks 165 billion for environmental cleanup in 
the 1990 fiscal year that begins oct 1 compared with 13 billion 
requested by bush 
the provision was part of a 1384 billion appropriations bill 
for energy and water development projects worked out late thursday 
after a full day of deliberation by house and senate negotiators 
the bill settled differences in the appropriations bills passed 
by the house in late june and by the senate in late july final 
approval by both houses is necessary before the measure goes to bush 
for his signature 
the administration had requested 1382 billion for the energy 
and water projects 
house and senate negotiators agreed to smaller sums than 
requested by bush for nuclear weapons activities 458 billion 
instead of 463 billion as well as smaller amounts for the 
nuclear materials production system 216 billion instead of 221 
billion 
congress has sought to push the energy department to speed 
cleanup of the radioactive and toxic wastes that have piled up at 
the nuclear weapons plants over the past four decades in some cases 
contaminating groundwater and soil near the facilities 
among the funds appropriated for waste cleanup was 276 million 
to bring the hanford nuclear reservation near richland wash into 
compliance with environmental standards and 291 million for a 
hanford vitrification facility designed to treat radioactive 
waste by turning it into a glasslike substance 
the measure also provides 55 million for environmental health 
and safety improvements at the feed materials production center 
near fernald ohio which processes uranium for the weapons program 
and has suffered extensive environmental damage 
an additional 267 million was appropriated for unspecified 
environmental and safety improvements at other plants 
among other energy projects to be financed in the coming budget 
year is a modification to the plutonium recovery facility known as 
building 371 at the rocky flats weapons plant near denver the bill 
appropriates 45 million for that work 
another provision of the bill earmarks 225 million for the 
superconducting supercollider a massive physics installation at 
which scientists plan to explore the nature of matter and energy 
the facility expected to cost 59 billion will be built in ellis 
county texas 
the bush administration had requested 250 million for the 
project for 1990 
