<TEXT>
india has agreed to withdraw its 
peacekeeping troops from sri lanka by end of the year a senior 
government official said saturday 
sri lankan officials have been trying for months to obtain the 
withdrawal of the troops who were sent to this island nation two 
years ago to quell ethnic violence 
an agreement on the new withdrawal date dec 31 was reached by 
indian and sri lankan officials during a meeting of nonaligned 
nations in belgrade yugoslavia the official said he spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
indian prime minister rajiv gandhi said friday in new delhi that 
an agreement had been reached on the pullout of the estimated 42000 
indian soldiers from sri lankas northeast but he refused to give 
details 
gandhi held at least two meetings in belgrade with sri lankan 
foreign minister ranjan wijeratne the sri lankan official said 
wijeratne apprised president ranasinghe premadasa of the indian 
proposals 
india had earlier proposed a withdrawal by the end of february 
sri lanka rejected the date triggering a dilplomatic deadlock 
the official said premadasa will consult his ministers on the new 
proposal on wednesday the government was very likely to approve 
the december withdrawal the official said 
india sent its troops under a peace accord it had sponsored to 
end a tamil insurrection for an independent nation in sri lankas 
northeast the accord signed on july 29 1987 offered tamils 
limited autonomy if rebel groups surrendered their weapons 
while most militias abided by the accord the dominant rebel 
group reneged on the pact and began attacking indian troops india 
despatched more soldiers to put down attacks by the liberation 
tigers of tamil eelam but the fighting continued and at least 1000 
indian soldiers have been killed 
in june premadasa asked india to withdraw all its troops by july 
29 gandhi refused saying a hasty pullout would lead to even more 
bloodshed 
a military showdown between the two countries however was 
averted when india agreed to make a token pullout on july 29 and 
subsequent limited withdrawals but the two countries failed to 
agree on a timetable for the complete withdrawal 
premadasa asked for the withdrawal to appease sinhalese radicals 
in the south who had launched a campaign of assassinations and 
terror to protest the accord and the presence of indian troops the 
militants say the indians compromise the countrys independence and 
they say the accord made too many concessions to the tamils 
tamils make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people they 
claim they are denied jobs and education by the sinhalese who make 
up 75 percent of the population and control the government and 
military 
india got involved because of the sympathies of its own 60 
million tamils for the rebel cause 
at least 10000 people have died in the 6yearold tamil war 
officials say at least 5000 have died in the 2yearold uprising by 
the sinhalese militants 
in a bid to end the violence premadasa has called a meeting of 
