<TEXT>
the bush administration is shunning covert 
intervention in nicaragua and instead is looking for money from 
congress to openly support the sandinista governments political 
opposition sources said saturday 
secretary of state james a baker iii is expected to speak with 
congressional leaders this week on prospects for a grant to the 
national endowment for democracy which would help the opposition 
campaign in the february elections said the sources speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the administration is considering asking for around 3 million to 
help violeta chamorro the prominent newspaper publisher chosen by 
several opposition parties as a consensus presidential candidate 
plus an unspecified amount for such things as voter registration 
election observers and repatriation said the sources 
carl gershman president of the national endowment said he did 
not know if congress or the administration was using the 3 million 
figure but my understanding is that it is roughly in the range of 
what some of the nicaraguans thought they need 
gershman said he has discussed new funding with members of 
congress and the ned board of directors which would approve how the 
money is spent will take it up at the end of the week 
the endowment is a private foundation created by congress in 1982 
to support democratic elections worldwide with money appropriated 
by congress for 1989 it got 158 million for its 
democracypromoting activities such as holding conferences and 
observing elections 
the organization since 1985 has provided support for la prensa 
the opposition newspaper led by mrs chamorro 
earlier this year congress approved 15 million for the 
endowment to promote democratic activity in nicaragua along with 
the same amount to pay for election observers under the auspices of 
the organization of american states 
we dont want to go the covert route said one administration 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity the official added 
the administration believes there would be no support in congress 
for covert action of the sort the cia used for years in nicaragua 
white house spokeman roman popadiuk declined to comment 
specifically on the administration plans 
the united states has long supported a return to democracy in 
nicaragua he said the national endowment for democracy has 
played a role in this process the administration is continuting to 
examine ways in which it can play a role in a fair and open 
election 
nicaraguas political opposition leaders signed an agreement with 
the sandinistas this summer agreeing there would be no secret 
funding of political activity 
under nicaraguan law half of any funds coming into the electoral 
system from outside the country must be given to the national 
supreme electoral council which oversees and monitors elections 
that means giving 6 million would have to be sent to nicaragua 
to ensure mrs chamorro got 3 million and some of the money would 
benefit the sandinista ticket under the national councils 
activities 
gershman said the us funds if approved would help even out an 
incredibly unbalanced situation in nicaragua where president 
daniel ortegas sandinistas control government resources 
theyre getting massive subsidies from the soviet bloc he 
said adding any us funds would be spent by his group in the 
spirit of trying to introduce a degree of fairness in the 
situation 
he said the opposition forces also are expected to seek campaign 
funds in europe and latin america 
the washington post which initially reported on the aid proposal 
saturday said the administration had been considering using the cia 
in the election in nicaragua but anticipated heavy congressional 
opposition 
after years of pinning its policy on the contra rebels that were 
fighting to oust the sandinistas the united states under president 
bush has endorsed diplomatic efforts underway to achieve peace 
with little sentiment in congress for renewing military aid bush 
agreed with congressional leaders on a 49 million nonlethal aid 
package to keep the contras in supplies and food until the election 
and to be used for repatriation where needed 
the last us military aid to the contras came in a 100 million 
package in 1986 that was accompanied by a lifting of restrictions on 
cia covert activity in nicaragua 
the presidents of nicaragua and four other central american 
nations reached agreement this year calling for disbandment of the 
contras coupled with moves toward democratic reform in nicaragua 
leading to the february elections 
