<TEXT>
wilkesbarre pa ap attorneys for a seventhday adventist 
couple convicted of starving their teenage son to death say they 
will appeal the verdict on grounds the boy was expressing his 
freedom of religion 
fourteenyearold eric cottam died jan 3 after the family went 
six weeks without food despite 3775 set aside by erics father a 
former seventhday adventist church pastor as a tithe for god 
a jury on friday deliberated for less than two hours before 
finding larry cottam and his wife leona cottam guilty of 
thirddegree murder two counts each of recklessly endangering 
another person and endangering the welfare of children in the cases 
of eric and their 12yearold daughter laura who since has been 
placed in a foster home 
they were under the care control and custody of their parents 
even though they may not want to eat the parents duty 
supercedes luzerne county judge gifford s cappelini said after 
the verdict 
the family had contended that each member agreed to the fast 
because of their religious convictions but cappelini ruled the 
cottams couldnt raise the childrens religious freedom in front of 
the jury 
al flora jr an attorney for the cottams said he plans to 
appeal on the grounds the childrens constitutional rights to 
religious freedom were not considered by the jury because of 
cappelinis ruling 
some of the issues involved in this case are novel ones 
flora said in asking the judge to allow the cottams to remain free 
on bail pending appeal they are issues that have not been taken 
up by our appellate courts 
cottam 39 and mrs cottam 38 remain free on 50000 bail 
each an anonymous benefactor posted bail for them aug 23 after 
they spent 230 days in custody following their jan 5 arraignment at 
mercy hospital 
after he was arrested cottam told police he couldnt spend the 
nearly 4000 in tithe money for food because it belonged to god 
spending it would have been akin to stealing he said 
seventhday adventists generally give 10 percent of their 
earnings as a tithe but a church official testified at the trial 
tithing was not a requirement for membership in the church 
mrs cottam testified she had several dollars saved as a tithe 
but also believed spending the money for food would have been the 
same as stealing 
neither cottam or his wife commented following the verdict nor 
did they testify during the trial 
no sentencing date has been set they face a maximum 28 years in 
prison 
eric cottam died in an upstairs bedroom of the familys modest 
twostory home in nuangola just south of this northeastern 
pennsylvania city his 5foot 9inch frame weighed 69 pounds 
a day later larry cottam went to a neighbors house to call 
police to his home he his wife and daughter were hospitalized for 
