<TEXT>
japanese investors get the headlines but the 
british have been on a buying spree for control of american 
companies that range from pineapple harvesters to typewriter makers 
standard oil co to burger king 
britain is the biggest foreign investor in the united states as 
it has been since colonial days what is less widely known is that 
britain is actually extending its lead over japan as well as the 
no3 netherlands and others 
british investors added 215 billion to their direct investments 
in the united states last year compared with additions of 142 
billion for japan commerce department figures show 
it appears that britains lead is widening even further in 1989 
grand metropolitan plc bought pillsbury co for 58 billion a 
deal that gave it such famous names as green giant haagendazs and 
burger king 
late last month bass plc agreed to buy holiday inns inc the 
nations innkeeper for 22 billion 
just this past week polly peck plc agreed to pay 875 million 
for a very large quantity of pineapples bananas papayas and 
mangoes the fresh fruit operations of rjr nabisco incs del monte 
foods inc 
economics would seem to give japan the edge over britain in 
buying into the united states japan accumulates huge sums of 
dollars through its bulging trade surplus with the united states 
which was greater than 50 billion last year in contrast britain 
ran a slender trade deficit with the united states in 1988 
but britain moves more boldly into the united states than japan 
does because of its history of internationalism the ease of dealing 
with another englishspeaking nation and the momentum generated by 
past dealings 
the japanese have the ability to be the largest acquirer in the 
united states but the british have the incentive said mark 
dixon editor of the britishamerican deal review in new york 
british companies are aggressive entrepreneurial 
international dixon said in terms of moving into foreign 
markets they are probably at the moment the most pioneering in the 
world 
in contrast dixon said the japanese are very cautious and 
they end up missing opportunities 
analysts say japanese investors get most of the attention from 
the news media and politicians because they are seen as a bigger 
threat to usbased competitors differences in race and culture 
probably add to the discomfort on both sides analysts add 
while japanese investment is concentrated in heavy industry and 
high technology for example steel autos and computers british 
investment is across the board 
john d rockefellers standard oil co is part of british 
petroleum co while robert maxwell owns macmillan books hanson plc 
owns smithcorona typewriters and bat industries owns farmers group 
insurance 
britains investment in the 1980s harks back to its investment in 
the 1890s when london bankers helped finance american railroads it 
is also a signal of the wave of the future said ethan harris 
an economist at morgan guaranty trust co in new york 
as businessmen become more familiar with each others markets 
theres more and more of these crossborder mergers and the natural 
leader in that would be two countries that have historical and 
business ties going back centuries harris said 
in other business and economic news this past week 
united airlines machinists union said its officials had been 
contacted by two buyout specialists seeking ual corp the parent of 
united and a prime takeover target the new parties are billionaire 
investor robert bass and takeover firm kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
meanwhile eastern airlines pilots said they had chosen a 
gladiator skip copeland an eastern captain based in new york 
to lead them after ousting the union leader who a month ago 
suggested they end their strike 
the dollar approached the peaks reached three months ago as 
bullish traders combated intervention by central banks which are 
trying to keep exchange rates stable at weeks end the dollar was 
trading just below 2 west german marks and a little above 147 
japanese yen 
ford motor co and saab scania ab of sweden said they were 
discussing closer cooperation in various areas of the automotive 
business saab scania didnt rule out a sale of a majority stake 
in its struggling car division a partial or full merger of the car 
divisions could mark the beginning of a consolidation in the 
worldwide automaking business 
